TY  - JOUR
AU  - Walther, Ansgar
AU  - White, Lucy
T1  - Rules versus Discretion in Bank Resolution
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/12/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa032
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 33
IS  - 12
SP  - 5594
EP  - 5629
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Recent reforms have given regulators broad powers to “bail-in” bank creditors during financial crises. We analyze efficient bail-ins and their implementation. To preserve liquidity, regulators must avoid signaling negative private information to creditors. Therefore, optimal bail-ins in bad times only depend on public information. As a result, the optimal policy cannot be implemented if regulators have wide discretion, due to an informational time-inconsistency problem. Rules mandating tough bail-ins after bad public signals, or contingent convertible (co-co) bonds, improve welfare. We further show that bail-in and bailout policies are complementary: if bailouts are possible, then discretionary bail-ins are more effective.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa032
ER  - 



