TY  - JOUR
AU  - Gofman, Michael
AU  - Segal, Gill
AU  - Wu, Youchang
T1  - Production Networks and Stock Returns: The Role of Vertical Creative Destruction
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/12/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa034
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 33
IS  - 12
SP  - 5856
EP  - 5905
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We examine empirically and theoretically the relation between firms’ risk and distance to consumers in a production network. We document two novel facts: firms farther away from consumers have higher risk premiums and higher exposure to aggregate productivity. We quantitatively explain these findings using a general equilibrium model featuring a multilayer production process. The economic force is “vertical creative destruction,” that is, positive productivity shocks to suppliers devalue customers’ assets-in-place, thereby lowering the cyclicality of downstream firms’ values. We show that vertical creative destruction varies with competition and firm characteristics and generates sizable cross-sectional differences in risk premiums.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa034
ER  - 



